1 Key takeaways

We analyzed change of baby names in USA over the years. In this project, we examined that:

  • How changed unique names over the years?
  • How changed traditional names and Modern Names over the years?
  • Find the most common name in a year by state.
  • Find the gender neutral names in states and which state is more gender equal.
  • Find the most used names based on state

2 Objectives:

  • Get raw data and arrange according to the result we want to learn
  • After put in order data visualize it and make INFERENCES
  • Finding more efficient reason with various data.
  • Using all dataset to find optimal solution.

4 Analysis

4.1 Unique Names

unique_names <- sqldf('SELECT Year, Gender, sum(Count)
                      FROM NationalNames
                      GROUP BY Year, Gender')
ggplot(unique_names) +
  geom_line(aes(Year, y = unique_names$`sum(Count)`/1000, color = Gender)) +
  labs(title = "Baby count based on gender over the years",
       x = "Year of observation",
       y = "Count")+
  theme_light() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(colour = "grey10", size = 10, angle = 45, hjust = 0.5, vjust = 0.5),
        axis.text.y = element_text(colour = "grey10", size = 10),
        text = element_text(size = 12))

4.3 Traditional Names vs.Â Modern Names

In this query shows us how names which were used only before 1990, and names which are used only after 1990 change over the year. Firstly, top 100 popular names should be found.

knitr::opts_chunk$set(echo = TRUE)
knitr::opts_knit$set(root.dir = "/Users/nilaykamar/Desktop/BDM/behzat_c")

library(sqldf)
Popular_names <- sqldf('select Name, sum(Count) as Count 
                From NationalNames
                group by Name
                order by Count desc
                LIMIT 10000') 

Traditionalnames <- sqldf('Select Name, sum(Count) as Count
                                    From NationalNames
                                    group by Name
                                    having max(Year) < 1990
                                    ORDER BY Count desc')

Modernames <- sqldf('Select Name, sum(Count) as Count
                                    From NationalNames
                                    group by Name
                                    having min(Year) > 1990
                    ORDER BY Count desc')

4.4 Most used names in states

This list shown us which names are most used in states, and which are the toppest in more than one states. Olivia seems to the most popular name in 2014.

knitr::opts_chunk$set(echo = TRUE)
knitr::opts_knit$set(root.dir = "/Users/nilaykamar/Desktop/BDM/behzat_c")

sqldf("SELECT name,count(name) 
                   from (Select name, year, MAX(count), State 
                         FROM StateNames 
                         Where year=2014 Group by State ) as maxi
                   group by name
                   having count(name) > 2
                   order by count(name) desc")
     name count(name)

2 William           9

4    Liam           6

4.5 Gender Neutral Names based on state

knitr::opts_chunk$set(echo = TRUE)
knitr::opts_knit$set(root.dir = "/Users/nilaykamar/Desktop/BDM/behzat_c")

Genderneutral <- sqldf('Select distinct(a.Name)
                        From (
                                Select Name
                                From NationalNames
                                Where Gender = "Male") as a INNER JOIN (
                                Select Name
                                From NationalNames
                                Where Gender = "Female") as b on a.Name = b.Name')
state_neutral <- sqldf('SELECT a.State, sum(a.Count) as Total
                       FROM StateNames as a, (Select distinct(a.Name)
                        From (
                                Select Name
                                From NationalNames
                                Where Gender = "Male") as a INNER JOIN (
                                Select Name
                                From NationalNames
                                Where Gender = "Female") as b on a.Name = b.Name) as b
                                WHERE b.Name = a.Name
                       GROUP BY a.State')
ggplot(state_neutral) +
  geom_bar(aes(State, Total/10000), stat = "identity", fill = "sky blue") +
  theme_classic() +
  labs(x="States", y="Sum of Gender Neutral Names(*10000)", title="Gender Neutral Names based on States") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle=90))

According to graph above, State â€œAZâ€ is the most gender neutral state.
